EXAMPLE 2: 6-CANDIDATE ELECTION (COMPLEX PREFERENCES)
======================================================================

============================================================
6-Candidate Election
============================================================
Options (6): ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Carol', 'Dave', 'Eve', 'Frank']

Win counts (Copeland scores):
  Alice               : 3/5 wins
  Dave                : 3/5 wins
  Eve                 : 3/5 wins
  Bob                 : 2/5 wins
  Carol               : 2/5 wins
  Frank               : 2/5 wins

No Condorcet winner (cyclic preferences exist)

OCF Analysis:
  3-cycles: 8, 5-cycles: 6
  Total odd cycles: 14
  H(T) exact: 41
  OCF: H = 1×1 + 14×2 + 2×4 = 37
  OCF MISMATCH: exact=41, OCF=37

Interpretation:
  H(T) = 41 consistent linear orderings
  More orderings = MORE ambiguity / LESS decisiveness
  Minimum possible H = 1 (totally transitive = perfect ranking)
  H for this n = 1: perfect transitivity

  3-cycle count = 14 (Condorcet paradoxes)
  Disjoint cycle pairs = 2 (compound paradoxes)
  Disjoint cycles: COMPOUND preference inconsistency

  H/H_max = 41/45 = 0.911
  => Highly ambiguous preferences (near maximum)

